					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tygently" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2038009); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2038009&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164228" alt="TyGently" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2038009)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tygently" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2038009); return false;" >TyGently</a></span> <span class="odate time_1466135241 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">17 Jun 2016 03:47</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2525074">
									

<p>There are good parts here, but I think the presentation takes a lot away from it. I think it would read as more cohesive if it were restructured without the bits at the beginning and end, instead converting them into the same format as the body, perhaps.</p>
<p>I feel like the story would be more believable if you took more time to explain the purpose of the expedition, and maybe even some time explaining how the ship works. Right now it mostly reads like you wanted to give the reader this information about what the rest of the galaxy is like, but didn't want to put much time in justifying how that information is recieved, so it comes across as convenient and a bit lazy.</p>
<p>The &quot;eldritch monster pregnancy&quot; is weird. Very cliche. I did like the note cobbled from other notes, but on the whole this mostly read as a narrative conveyance of a theory that's already quite well-known.</p>

							</div>

								
					
